<HEADLINE>
Early morning Barley (high beta glucan content) reduce glucose and insulin demands all day
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<POST>
<POSTER> &quot;ra...@val.com&quot; &lt;ra...@val.com&gt; </POSTER>
<POSTDATE> 2007-09-05T22:05:00 </POSTDATE>
Here's an interesting report concerning early morning whole barley and
insulin and glucose response through out the day.

http://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2007/09/070905095324.htm

What's interesting is that the purposed mechanism is not just from
delayed glucose absorbtion, but the conversion of fiber by gut
bacteria to butyrate. The butyrate, when absorbed, has all sorts of
positve benefits.

There lots of coaborating evidence such as:

http://care.diabetesjournals.org/cgi/content/abstract/19/8/831

This also fits in well with the study of Japanese prisoners feed a
high barley diet reported a few weeks ago to the group.

Some might ask why not just have a low carb, high protein breakfast
thereby avoiding the much dietary glucose.
As far as avoiding dietary glucose this reasoning is correct, but your
still straining your poor worn out beta cells to pump out insulin.
This is especially true for beef and diary products contain whey. If
you really want to beat up your pancreas low carb whey shake.
</POST>
